Subject: mental disorder
Value: A disease that involves a psychological or behavioral pattern generally associated with subjective distress or disability that occurs in an individual, and which are not a part of normal development or culture.

Subject: mental disorder
Value: Clinically significant behavioural and/or cognitive pathology.

Subject: insomnia
Value:
A subjective complaint of difficulty falling or staying asleep or poor sleep quality.

Subject: insomnia
Value:
A subjective complaint of difficulty falling or staying asleep or poor sleep quality.

DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: diagnosis of mental disease
Value: A diagnosis asserting the presence of an instance of a mental disease in a given organsim.

Subject: manifestation of a mental disease
Value: A bodily feature of an organism that is (a) a deviation from clinical normality that is the realization of a mental disease and is (b) observable.

Subject: process addiction
Value: An addiction to a process, which might be a behaviour, such as gambling, or procrastination.

Subject: gambling addiction
Value: A process addiction in which the patient compulsively gambles.

Subject: shopping addiction
Value: A process addiction in which the person compulsively performs shopping activities.

Subject: addiction to use of a sunbed
Value: A process addiction in which the subject compulsively makes use of a sunbed.

Subject: dissociative fugue
Value: fuga disociativa

Subject: sexual desire disorder
Value:
F52.0 ( Hypoactive Sexual Desire Disorder)
F52.10 ( Sexual Aversion Disorder)

Subject: primary sleep disorder: dyssomnia
Value:
Primary disorders of initiating or maintaining sleep or of excessive sleepiness and are characterized by abnormalities in the amount, quality or timing of sleep.

DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: primary sleep disorder: parasomnia
Value:
Disorders characterised by abnormal behavioural or physiological events occurring in association with sleep, specific sleep stages, or sleep-wake transitions.

DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: cataplexy
Value: <a sudden and transient episode of loss of muscle tone accompanied by full conscious awareness, often triggered by emotions such as laughing, crying, terror, etc.http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cataplexy>

Subject: delusion
Value:
Erroneous beliefs that usually involve a misinterpretation of perceptions or experiences. (their content may include a variety of themes (e.g., persecutory, referential, somatic, religious, or grandiose).


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: apprehension
Value: Anxiety or fear that something bad or unpleasant will happen.

Subject: delirium
Value:
Is characterised by disturbance of consciousness and changes in cognition (memory deficit, disorientation, and language and perceptual disturbances).

The patient often shows a reduced ability to focus, sustain or shift attention and exhibits disorganized patterns of thinking, as manifested by rambling, irrelevant, or incoherent speech. At times patients show a reduced level of consciousness and disturbances in the cycle of sleep and waking.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: enuresis
Value:
The habitual voiding of urine during the day or night into one's clothes, bed, or floor. The behaviour is generally involuntary, but in rare situations it may be intentional.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: encopresis
Value:
Involves repeated defecating onto one's clothes, the floor or other inappropriate places.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: compulsion
Value:
The need to perform acts or to dwell on thoughts to reduce anxiety.

\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: obsession
Value:
An intrusive and repetitive thought or image that produce anxiety.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: catatonic behaviour
Value:
Marked motor abnormalities including motoric immobility (i.e., catalepsy or stupor), certain types of excessive motor activity (apparently purposeless agitation not influenced by external stimuli), extreme negativism (apparent motiveless resistance to instructions or attempts to be moved) or mutism, posturing or stereotyped movements, and echolalia or echopraxia. 


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: depersonalization
Value:
An alteration in the perception or experience of the self so that one feels detached from, and as if one is an outside observer of, one's mental processes or body (e.g., feeling like one is in a dream).


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: derealization
Value:
An alteration in the perception or experience of the external world so that it seems strange or unreal (e.g., people may seem unfamiliar or mechanical).


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: flashback
Value:
The recurrence of a memory, feeling, or perceptual experience from the past.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: hallucination
Value:
Sensory perception that has the compelling sense of reality of a true perception but that occurs without external stimulation of the relevant sensory organ.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: magical thinking
Value:
The erroneous belief that one's thoughts, words, or actions will cause or prevent a specific outcome in some way that defies commonly understood laws of cause and effect.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: insomnia
Value:
A subjective complaint of difficulty falling or staying asleep or poor sleep quality.

DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: anxiety
Value:
The apprehensive anticipation of future danger or misfortune accompanied by a feeling of dysphoria or somatic symptoms of tension. 


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: dissociation
Value:
A disruption in the usually integrated functions of consciousness, memory, identity, or perception of the environment. 
The disturbance may be sudden or gradual, transient or chronic.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: flight of ideas
Value:
A nearly continuous flow of accelerated speech with abrupt changes from topic to topic that are usually based on understandable associations, distracting stimuli, or plays on words. When severe, speech may be disorganised and incoherent.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: grandiosity
Value:
An inflated appraisal of one's worth, power, knowledge, importance, or identity. When extreme, grandiosity may be of delusional proportions.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: phobia
Value:
A persistent, irrational fear of a specific object, activity, or situation (the phobic stimulus) that results in a compelling desire to avoid it. 


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: homicidal ideations
Value: homicidal thoughts

Subject: agoraphobia
Value: <Extreme fear of being in public places or open spaces from which escape may be difficult or embarrassing.http://www.apa.org/research/action/glossary.aspx>

Subject: fixation
Value: <A state in which a person remains attached to objects or activities more appropriate for an earlier stage of psychosexual development.http://www.apa.org/research/action/glossary.aspx>

Subject: cocaine bugs
Value:
The sensation of tiny creatures crawling over the cocaine user's skin.

Psychopharmacology Drugs, the Brain, and Behavior (Jerrold S. Meyer, Linda F. Quenzer)

Subject: suicide
Value: The act of intentionally causing one's own death.

Subject: manic episode
Value:
Period of abnormally and persistently elevated, expansive, or irritable mood, lasting at least 1 week (or any duration if hospitalization is necessary). 

DSM-IV-TR

Subject: delayed sleep-phase syndrome
Value:
Disorder in which the major sleep episode is delayed in relation to the desired clock time, resulting in symptoms of sleep-onset insomnia or difficulty in awakening at the desired time.


The International Classification of Sleep Disorders, Revised. Diagnostic and Coding Manual
(American Academy of Sleep Medicine in association with the European Sleep Research Society, Japanese Society of Sleep Research and Latin American Sleep Society)

Subject: hypomanic episode
Value: Is defined as a distinct period during which there is an abnormally and persistently elevated, expansive, or irritable mood that last at least 4 days.

Subject: nightmare
Value: Dream that can cause a strong emotional response from the mind, typically fear or horror, but also despair, anxiety and great sadness. The dream may contain situations of danger, discomfort, psychological or physical terror.

Subject: binge-eating disorder
Value: The essential features are recurrent episodes of being eating associated with subjective and behavioural indicators of impaired control over, and significant distress about, the binge eating and the absence of the regular use of inappropriate compensatory behaviours (such as self-induced vomiting, misuse of laxatives and other medications, fasting, and excessive exercise) that are characteristic of Bulimia Nervosa.

Subject: caffeine intoxication
Value:
The essential feature of caffeine intoxication is recent consumption of caffeine and five or more symptoms that develop during, or shortly after caffeine use.

DSM-IV-TR

Subject: caffeine intoxication
Value:
- Restlessness
- Nervousness 
- Excitement 
- Insomnia
- Flushed face
- Diuresis
- Gastrointestinal disturbance 
- Muscle twitching
- Rambling flow of thought and speech
- Tachycardia or cardiac arrhythmia
- Periods of inexhaustibility
- Psychomot agitation

Subject: grossly disorganized behavior
Value: Behavior that may manifest itself in a variety of ways, ranging from childlike silliness to unpredictable agitation.

Subject: suicidal ideations
Value: suicidal thoughts

Subject: affective flattening
Value: Is characterized by the person's face appearing immobile and unresponsive, with poor eye contact and reduced body language.

Subject: alogia
Value: Is manifested  by brief, laconic, empty replies.

Subject: defense mechanism
Value:
Automatic psychological process that protects the individual against anxiety and from awareness of internal or external stressors or dangers.


DSM-IV-TR (american Psychiatric Association)

Subject: repression
Value: <The basic defense mechanism by which painful or guilt-producing thoughts, feelings, or memories are excluded from conscious awareness.http://www.apa.org/research/action/glossary.aspx>

Subject: reaction formation
Value:
Repression of dangerous impulses, followed by converting them to their direct opposite.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: projection
Value:
Ridding oneself of threatening desires or thoughts by attributing them to others.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: rationalization
Value:
Explaining one's behavior by giving well-thought-out and socially acceptable reasons that do not happen to be the real ones.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: regression
Value:
A retreat to an earlier developmental level that demands less mature responses and aspirations.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue.

Subject: paranoia
Value: Thought process believed to be heavily influenced by anxiety or fear, often to the point of irrationality and delusion.

Subject: abstinence syndrome
Value:
Condition characterised by distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other areas of functioning, or physical or emotional symptoms such as shaking, irritability, and inability to concentrate after reducing or ceasing intake of a substance.


\"Understanding abnormal behavior\". David Sue, Derald Wing Sue, Stanley Sue

Subject: dysphoria
Value: <Feeling of emotional and mental discomfort as a symptom of discontentment, restlessness, dissatisfaction, malaise, depression, anxiety or indifference.http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysphoria >

Subject: premenstrual syndrome
Value: <Premenstrual syndrome (PMS) is a generic term which includes a broad group of emotional, behavioral and physical symptoms that occur for several days to several weeks before menses and subside following the menstrual period.Premenstrual syndrome and premenstrual dysphoric disorder: definitions and diagnosis. ( Ellen W Freeman)>

Subject: hyperarousal
Value:
State of increased psychological and physiological tension marked by such effects as reduced pain tolerance, anxiety, exaggeration of startle responses, insomnia, fatigue and accentuation of personality traits. 

Dorland's Medical Dictionary for Health Consumers.

Subject: social dysfunction
Value: The inability to perform in the interaction with other people.

Subject: craving (withdrawal)
Value: <Psychological urge to administer a discontinued medication or recreational drug.http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craving_%28withdrawal%29>

Subject: disorientation
Value:
A state of mental confusion as to time, place, or identity.

Value: The repetition of a particular response, such as a word, phrase, or gesture, despite the absence or cessation of a stimulus, usually caused by brain injury or other organic disorder.

Subject: thought blocking
Value: Phenomenon that occurs occurs when a person's speech is suddenly interrupted by silences that may last a few seconds to a minute or longer.
